], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6736014485359192, "span": {"begin": 1270, "end": 1277}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2904"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GluR&epsilon;2+/+)", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8860745429992676, "span": {"begin": 1310, "end": 1328}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.949806809425354, "span": {"begin": 1329, "end": 1333}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998082160949707, "span": {"begin": 1367, "end": 1371}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016202"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NMDA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.997930645942688, "span": {"begin": 1401, "end": 1405}}, {"id": ["mesh:D015763"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "APV", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9955945611000061, "span": {"begin": 1461, "end": 1464}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016202"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NMDA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997219443321228, "span": {"begin": 1483, "end": 1487}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Ca2+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9967071413993835, "span": {"begin": 1509, "end": 1513}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2904"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GluR&epsilon;2&minus;/&minus;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7890481948852539, "span": {"begin": 1546, "end": 1575}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9480444192886353, "span": {"begin": 1576, "end": 1580}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016202"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NMDA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991549253463745, "span": {"begin": 1616, "end": 1620}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2902"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NMDA receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9748392105102539, "span": {"begin": 1616, "end": 1630}}], "text": "The relationship between KE (NMDARs, Inhibition) and KE (Calcium influx, Decreased) is plausible as the function evaluation of NMDA receptors is commonly carried out by measurement of intracellular influx of Ca2+ upon NMDA receptor stimulation by agonist. Calcium imaging techniques have been extensively utilized to investigate the relationship between these two KEs. Almost 15% of the current through NMDA receptors is mediated by Ca2+ under physiological conditions (Higley and Sabatini, 2012).  It has been shown that less than five and, occasionally only a single NMDA receptor opens under physiological conditions, causing a total Ca2+ influx of about 6000 ions into a dendritic spine head reaching a concentration of &sim;10 &micro;M (Higley and Sabatini, 2012). However, the majority of the ions are rapidly eliminated by binding Ca2+ proteins, reaching &sim;1 &micro;M of free Ca2+ concentration (Higley and Sabatini, 2012).  In rat primary forebrain cultures, the intracellular Ca2+ increases after activation of the NMDA receptor and this increase is blocked when the cells are cultured under Ca2+ free conditions, demonstrating that the NMDA-evoked increase in intracellular Ca2+ derives from extracellular and not intracellular sources (Liu et al., 2013).  Neurons in brain slices from wild-type (GluR&epsilon;2+/+) mice showed increase of intracellular Ca2+ in the presence of 100 &mu;M NMDA that was completely inhibited after exposure to 100 mM APV. In contrast, the NMDA-mediated increase in Ca2+ was absent in brain slices from GluR&epsilon;2&minus;/&minus; mice that do not possess any functional NMDA receptors in the developing neocortex (Okada et al., 2003).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:24:14 +0000 2026"}